				  <h3>
    					LA 311: A Case Study -- 'Mobile Image' Driven Customer Services: A Model for 21st Century Criminal Justice Information Services?
    				</h3>
				  <p>
						This presentation will explore the latest information submission and management models occurring across the financial services industry and now moving rapidly into government services models like 311. The initial implementations within LA Water & Power enable 'image capture and submission' from citizen mobile devices for street repair and permit request submissions, approval and tracking. This model can provide a close parallel for the Public Safety & Justice communities.
Taking 'Mobile Bank Deposits' to the next step -- triggering Public Safety processes:</p>
				  <ul>
					  <li>
					    Citizen Watch 'Suspect Image Capture' accelerated evidence gathering					  </li>
					  <li>
					    eFiling Court Documents from an attorney's iPhone & Android device					  </li>
					  <li>
					    Integrated 'Criminal Intelligence Dashboards' tying Web, Social Media, & Traditional Information together					  </li>
				  </ul>
					<p>Additionally, this presentation will demonstrate how this approach parallels and integrates with Oracle's 'Integrated
					  Policing Platform'. IPP provides world class abilities to manage a complex set of information associated with an investigation, manage secure access to the data so that only relevant team members can see it, and proactively manage the relevant business process flows, to ensure that the right actions are taken at each step of the investigation, while providing an audit trail to support the validity of information & actions in subsequent stages of the legal process.					  </p>
