					<h3>
    					New York State Integrated Justice Portal
    				</h3>
					<p>The New York State (NYSPIN replacement) Integrated Justice Portal (IJP) is one of the most comprehensive, and leading implementation of NIEM and SOA standards, and was the 2011 Best of NIEM award winner.
The IJP is an example of an Information Sharing Environment where services from multiple mission partners are deployed in a shared, highly available infrastructure, and enables access to real-time criminal history; department of motor vehicles queries across all 50 states; maintains local 'hot files' of stolen property like vehicles, boats, securities, warrants and missing persons reports, etc. while updating this information in real-time on the FBI NCIC databases; and other investigative information data retrieval from federal and state information systems.
The business objectives of the upgrade were to:</p>
					<ul>
					  <li> 
					    improve the availability of justice information to the user community by providing a single point of access to criminal justice information from multiple sources</li>
					  <li> 
					    improve end user processes by reusing existing data and reduce cycle time by presenting aggregated information; reduce redundancies</li>
					  <li> 
					    comply with FBI CJIS security standards, while improving existing response times and current levels of accuracy and completeness of information					  </li>
				  </ul>
					<p>Among the chief technology objectives were to implement:</p>
					<ul>
					  <li> 
					    a multi-year information technology (IT) strategy to replace the legacy systems					  </li>
					  <li>
					    implement standards-based technology and enable a mobile workforce					  </li>
					  <li>
					    provide an information sharing environment that grows as the information needs and sources grow; either by adding new data repositories, or expanding the environment to enable more agencies to co-host their business services </li>
				  </ul>
